Note:The associated shiny App has been tested with R version 4.0.3. Image rendering problem may occur on the App with lower versions

Creation of Shiny application using AirBnB Paris data

Below is the scope of the application:

  1. Relationship between apartment price and apartment features
  2. Number of apartments per owner
  3. Renting price per city quarter
  4. Visit frequency of the different quarters according to time

In order to be able to create the shiny application,the data need to be analyzed.

Below are the steps required to carry out the task:

  1. Loading of available data in to ‘R’ environment
  2. Joining of the 2 data sets provided.
  3. Cleaning the dataset
  4. Extracting the relevant data based on the required variables and # of obs
  5. Plotting the appropriate charts with relevant variables and providing comments
  6. Producing the app files, which requires coding for both server and ui

=============Data cleaning======

Using the Zipcode to extract Paris dataset

Since the focus is on Paris data, the data has to be filtered for Paris City. This requires the use of ‘filter’ function and the filtered data set will be assigned to AirBnB_Paris

AirBnB_Paris = filter(df_AirBnB, zipcode == 75001 | zipcode == 75002 | zipcode ==  75003 | zipcode ==  75004 | zipcode ==  75006 | zipcode ==  75007 | zipcode ==  75008 | zipcode ==  75009 | zipcode ==  75010 | zipcode ==  75011 | zipcode ==  75012 | zipcode ==  75013 | zipcode ==  75014 | zipcode ==  75015 | zipcode ==  75016 | zipcode ==  75116 | zipcode ==  75017 | zipcode ==  75018 | zipcode ==  75019 | zipcode ==  75020)

Extracting required columns

AirBnB <- select(AirBnB_Paris,Apartment_id=id,Apartmentname=name,host_id,host_name,
    property_type,city,price,room_type,bed_type,reviews_per_month,cancellation_policy,date,review_scores_communication,review_scores_cleanliness)

Now, the extracted data set ‘AirBnBdfe’ has 638111 obs. and 14 variables.

Data type conversion for price and date

AirBnB$price <- as.numeric(gsub("[\\$,]","",AirBnB$price))#convert price to numeric
AirBnB$date <-as.Date(AirBnB$date)#convert date to date type

Removing special character from host_name column

AirBnB$host_name <- gsub("[[:punct:]]", "", AirBnB$host_name)#Removing punctuation mark
AirBnB$host_name <- str_replace_all(AirBnB$host_name, "[^[:alnum:]]", "")#Delete non-alphanumeric

Missing data removal and replacement

-Replace the NAs review_scores_communication and review_scores_cleanliness with median value -Remove NAs from date column

# Exclude the NA from date 
AirBnB <- AirBnB[complete.cases(AirBnB$date),]
# Return the column names containing missing Values
list_na <- colnames(AirBnB)[ apply(AirBnB, 2, anyNA) ]
#Replace the median value for review_score_communication and review_scores_cleanliness
replace_median <- apply(AirBnB[,colnames(AirBnB)%in% list_na],2,median,na.rm=TRUE)
AirBnB$review_scores_communication <-AirBnB$review_scores_communication %>% replace_na(10)
AirBnB$review_scores_cleanliness <-AirBnB$review_scores_cleanliness %>% replace_na(9)

Creating new columns for Year and Month Abbreviations

AirBnB <- AirBnB %>%mutate(Year = as.numeric(format(AirBnB$date,"%Y")),
                           Month = as.numeric(format(AirBnB$date,"%m")))
mymonths <-c("Jan","Feb","Mar",
              "Apr","May","Jun",
              "Jul","Aug","Sep",
              "Oct","Nov","Dec")

#add abbreviated month name
AirBnB$MonthAbb <- mymonths[ AirBnB$Month ]

==============Analysis and Visualisation=========

Question 1:Relationship between prices and apartment

Statistical Analysis to show the relationship between the prices and room_type

Price_apartment <- AirBnB %>%select(price,room_type,property_type,Apartmentname)%>%filter(property_type=='Apartment') %>%group_by(room_type)
        ggplot(Price_apartment)+geom_boxplot(aes(x=room_type,y= price),fill = "coral",colour = "#3366FF")+
       # scale_size_area() +
        labs(
        x="Room_type" ,
        y="Prices ($)" ,
        title="Statistical Analysis of prices apartment features by room_type")

The boxplot here shows that there are few (biased) price values in the dataset which have significant effect on the statistics. It is therefore necessary to remove these entries in order to obtain more accurate statistics. Based on the plots above, a threshold of 200 dollars is set and values above this are treated as outliers.

Remove of Outlier from the dataset

outlier <- AirBnB%>%select(price,room_type)%>%filter(room_type=="Entire home/apt",price>200)

allentirehome <- AirBnB%>%select(price,room_type)%>%filter(room_type=="Entire home/apt")

outlier_ratio = dim(outlier)[1]/dim(allentirehome)[1]*100

outlier_ratio
## [1] 5.231852

Only 5% of the entire dataset is has prices above the 200 dollars threshold inidicating that statistics after outlier removal are accurate.

Box plot after outlier removal from the dataset

Price_apartment <- AirBnB %>%select(price,room_type,property_type,Apartmentname)%>%filter(property_type=='Apartment',price <200) %>%group_by(room_type)
        ggplot(Price_apartment)+geom_boxplot(aes(x=room_type,y= price),fill = "coral",colour = "#3366FF")+
       # scale_size_area() +
        labs(
        x="Room_type" ,
        y="Prices ($)" ,
        title="Statistical Analysis of prices apartment features by room_type")

From the boxplot, we can see that entire apartments and shared rooms have the highest and lowest median prices, respectively. Compare to the other two types, entire homes have significantly larger variation.

Statistics (Mean,Meadian and standard deviation) for price based on room type

summaryprice <- Price_apartment %>%summarise(
                                  mean=mean(price,na.rm=TRUE),
                                  median=median(price,na.rm=TRUE),
                                  sd =sd(price,na.rm=TRUE))
summaryprice
## # A tibble: 3 x 4
##   room_type        mean median    sd
## * <fct>           <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 Entire home/apt  87.6     80  34.7
## 2 Private room     51.6     50  17.3
## 3 Shared room      34.8     33  11.6

The table shows that the rent price for private rooms have the highest average,median and standard deviation. A graphical visualization of the statistics is performed below ### Visualisation of the statistical summaries

 plot.new()
  cols <- c('red','blue','green');
  ylim <- c(0,max(summaryprice[c('mean','median','sd')])*1.8);
  par(lwd=6);
  barplot(
    t(summaryprice[c('mean','median','sd')]),
    beside=T,
    ylim=ylim,
    border=cols,
    col='coral',
    names.arg=summaryprice$room_type,
    xlab='Apartment Type',
    ylab='Price Statistics ($)',
    legend.text=c('Average Price','Median Price','Standard deviation'),
    args.legend=list(text.col=cols,col=cols,border=cols,bty='n'),
    
  )
  box();

Question2:Number of apartments per owner

NumberOfApartmentsPerOwner <- AirBnB %>% select(Apartment_id,host_id,host_name,property_type)%>%
  filter(property_type == "Apartment") %>%
  group_by(host_name) %>%
  summarise(Total=n_distinct(Apartment_id))%>%arrange(desc(Total))
datatable(NumberOfApartmentsPerOwner,colnames = c('Name_of_owner'=2,'Number_of_Apartment'=3))

The table allows visualization of the number of apartments owned by each owner as contained in the data set.

Scatter plot for number of apartment per owner

ggplot(NumberOfApartmentsPerOwner,aes(Total,Total))+geom_point(aes(colour ="red"))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")+
  labs(
    x ="Number of apartment per owner",
    y ="Number of apartment per owner",
    title = "Scatter plot for number of apartment per owner"
  )

Grouping the number of apartment per owners

Name <-list(unique(AirBnB$host_name)) 

NumberOfApartmentsPerOwner <- AirBnB %>% select(Apartment_id,host_id,host_name,property_type)%>%
    filter(property_type == "Apartment") %>%
    group_by(host_name) %>%
    summarise(Total=n_distinct(Apartment_id))%>%arrange(desc(Total))
num_list <- rep(0,20)

for (i in 1:20){
  if (i < 1){
    num_list[i] = length(which(NumberOfApartmentsPerOwner$Total == i))
  }
  else{
    num_list[i] = length(which(NumberOfApartmentsPerOwner$Total >= i))
  }
}
df_number_apartment <- data.frame(num_list,Number_per_owner=c(1:20))
   ggplot(df_number_apartment,aes(Number_per_owner,num_list))+ geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill='coral')+
   
   labs(
    x="Number of apartment per owner" ,
    y="Number of persons" ,
    title="Analysis of number of apartments per owner: x indicates >= x")

This bar plot shows that significant number of owners have below 10 apartments with the largest percentage having only one apartment.

A box plot of the price statistics for all arrondisements. Prices range from 38 dollars to slightly below 500 dollars with an average of around 300 dollars.

Average prices per Arrondisement

Question4:Visit frequency of the different quarrters according to time.

Frequency visit for per year

frequency_years_visit <-AirBnB%>%select(city,Year)%>%filter(city%in% target)
         ggplot(data = frequency_years_visit) + 
         geom_bar(aes(y = factor(city),fill=factor(Year)))+  
            guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse=TRUE))+
         labs(
         x="Frequency" ,
         y="Arrondissements" ,
        fill="Year",
        title="Visit frequency per year from 2012 -- 2016")

The frequency of visit to the arrondisements appear to increase each year from 2013 to 2016. For most of the apartments, visits in 2012 and 2013 were limited compared to subsequent years.

Visit frequency per month

Frequency_month_visit <-AirBnB%>%select(MonthAbb,city)%>%
          filter(city%in% target)%>%arrange(MonthAbb)
ggplot(data = Frequency_month_visit) + 
geom_bar(aes(y = factor(city),fill=factor(MonthAbb)))+
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Month", labels =c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar","Apr","May","Jun","Jul","Aug","Sep","Oct","Nov","Dec"))+
  scale_size_area() +
  labs(
  x="Frequency" ,
  y="Arrondissements" ,
  fill="month",
  title="Visit frequency per month from 2012 -- 2016")

The number of visits is significantly higher between June and August which appear reasonable considering that this is usual summer holiday season in Europe.
